snippet.textDisplay:
Uhhhhm, it's NOT going away anytime soon. What's most likely to happen, is it will go into a bit of remission as the weather warms up. Then, once we get to October-December, it will spike hard again and most likely become a worldwide problem in the realm of what the Spanish Flu was. That killed what, a tenth of the entire world population?

In the US, all this talk about staying home and calling in to work sick is a pipe dream. The last people that should be working, min wage food service employees, can't afford to take a day off. So, it's a nice thought until you realize how bad the US healthcare and sick time/pto benefits are. If you can even call them benefits....

The min wage McDonald's worker who can't afford a single day off will come to work sick and infect not just the customers, but the other workers as well. This rings true too. If i had to guess, around 60% of the population in the US can't afford to take a day off of work without it severely messing up their finances and budget. On top of that, even if they do get out of work because of the virus, they can't afford to see a doctor or stay in the hospital to be monitored. Places like Walmart, Amazon, food service industry, etc. Their workers are interacting with, and being around thousands of people, everyday at work. They will infect eachother and the businesses customers as well, all because those places refuse to provide their employees benefits that are actually worth a damn.

It really seems like this will get out of control fast. Not only is our government unprepared because numb nuts Trump halted a full 80% of the federal funding for being prepared for a pandemic/epidemic scenarios a few years ago. The middle class is in such bad shape, most of them can't afford a day off of work, or an unexpected hospital bill. Even when that individual is fully insured. I hope this opens people's eyes to the importance of national healthcare.
